Acclaimed for his colorful and dynamic depictions of everyday life, labor, and the land, Benton focused on creating a popular, accessible, and distinctively American kind of modern art. In 1928, he and Bill Hayden, one of his Art Students’ League students, went on the road for several months.

Name: Thomas Hart Benton
Designation: American Regionalist - Muscular Painter of the Heartland
Bio: Thomas Hart Benton (1889-1975), American painter and muralist who led the Regionalist art movement. From Missouri, he rejected European abstraction for dynamic depictions of American life, particularly the Midwest and South. His flowing, almost sculptural style captured the energy of American labor, folklore, and landscape. Teacher of Jackson Pollock, he paradoxically influenced abstract expressio...
